  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 삼승(三乘) : '
    value: 세 가지의 교법, 성문승(聲聞乘)ㆍ연각승(緣覺乘)ㆍ보살승(菩薩乘). 승(乘)은 타고 옮긴다는 뜻으로 중생이 불법을 타고 고해(苦海)를 넘어 피안에 이른다는 뜻.
  - key: '[주-D002] 쌍림(雙林) : '
    value: 석가여래가 세상을 떠난 곳.
  - key: '[주-D003] 삼관(三觀) : '
    value: 천태종(天台宗)에서 세운 공관(空觀)ㆍ가관(假觀)ㆍ중관(中觀)의 세 가지 관법인데, 특히 천태종에서 주장한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 묘종(妙宗) : '
    value: 《묘종초(妙宗鈔)》라고도 함. 《관무량수경(觀無量壽經)》 가운데 뽑은 《묘종초》의 약칭.
  - key: '[주-D005] 법화삼매(法華三昧) : '
    value: 기도하고 참회(懺悔)하여 죄를 없애기 위해 수도하는 불사(佛事).
  - key: '[주-D006] 사중(四衆) : '
    value: 중들의 종류, 비구(比丘)ㆍ비구니(比丘尼)ㆍ우파새(優婆塞)ㆍ우파이(優婆夷).
  - key: '[주-D007] 학림(鶴林) : '
    value: 석가여래가 입적할 때 신사 쌍수(雙樹)의 숲이 학 모양으로 변했다는 고사이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 지자(智者) : '
    value: 즉 중국 수(隋)나라 시대 천태종의 조사(祖師) 지의(智顗), 자는 당시에 덕안(德安)이며, 속성은 진(陣)씨로서 지자선사라 했다.
english:
  title: Stele Inscription and Preface for National Master Wonmyo of Baekryeon Monastery on Mount Mandok
  author: Choe Ja
  language: eng
  text: "The Tathagata appeared in this world for one great purpose and cause. He widely expounded the various sutras, yet the great and small, the provisional and the real, could not be unified in a single thread. When the occasion met the time, like an ulcer about to burst, he then proclaimed the wonderful Lotus, embracing the nine realms and three vehicles, leading all into the one Buddha-vehicle. The long-hidden aspirations were at last fully revealed with nothing remaining unsaid.\n\nWhen the Buddha entered nirvana at the Twin Grove and the profound teachings began to scatter, only the Great Bodhisattva Nagarjuna grieved at this and expounded the ultimate principle of the teaching, breaking through all contrary views. He opened the profound gate of the three contemplations—a lineage continued by Hui-wen and Hui-ssu, renewed by the Great Master Zhiyi who struck the bell of dharma anew, gathered in its final form by Master Zhangian, transmitted by the two great ones, preserved by You-xi, and recorded by Pi-ling. The dharma tradition was complete and fit to be practiced in the world.\n\nIn our Goryeo, masters like Hyuangwang, Uitong, Chekwan, Dukseon, Jijong, and Uicheon crossed the seas to inquire and brought back the meaning of the Tiantai three contemplations, spreading them throughout our land and bringing blessings to our nation—a heritage long established. Yet to open the Samantabhadra dojo and widely encourage the chanting of sutras had not been accomplished until our Master came.\n\nOur Master appeared at a time when the dharma was declining. He erected a great dharma banner that awakened the ignorant masses and awakened faith without roots, causing the teachings of the patriarchs to flourish and spread throughout the realm. Could this not be the fruition of original vows, manifesting in the degenerate age as one sent by the Tathagata to accomplish the Tathagata's work?\n\nThe Master's dharma name was Ryoese; his personal name, Anpin. His lay surname was Seo. He was from Shinbeon County. His father, Biljoong, served as a local magistrate; his mother, also of the Seo clan, was from the same district. He was born in the winter, the tenth month of the Daejeong era. From birth he was acute and luminous, with a commanding presence that bore the dignity of advanced age even in youth.\n\nAt twelve he left home to study under Reverend Gyunjeong at Cheonrak Monastery in Gangyang, becoming a novice and first encountering the Tiantai teachings. At this time, scholar Im Jongbi, having become magistrate of the region, met him once and declared: \"The dharma has found a worthy vessel.\" At twenty-three he passed the monastic examination and devoted himself entirely to the teachings. After several years of studying at various lecture halls, he fully grasped the intricate principles and already had gained eminence in his tradition.\n\nIn the spring of the third year of Seungan, he went to the capital where a dharma assembly was held at Gophung Monastery. Renowned monks gathered like clouds and heterodox views arose like swarming bees. Our Master ascended the dharma seat and delivered a single exposition. All shrank back in submission, none daring to object.\n\nBy nature loving mountains and streams, though he remained in the ordained community, his heart lay elsewhere. That autumn, with a dozen companions, he traveled to famous temples. He first stayed at Jangyon Monastery on Yeongdong Mountain, where he opened a teaching hall and earnestly guided students. Those seeking instruction came in great numbers.\n\nAt this time the Oxherder of Jegye was at Gongsan meeting Buddha's Cliff. Hearing of the Master's reputation, he secretly felt a spiritual kinship and sent an inscribed verse encouraging him toward the practice of meditation:\n\n*Waves churned, the moon obscured—*\n*The deep chamber glows brighter still.*\n*I urge you to straighten the vessel of mind,*\n*Lest the nectar of grace be spilled.*\n\nThe Master read these words with satisfaction and hastened to study under him, becoming his dharma friend and assisting in the propagation of the way. After some years, the Oxherder moved his community south, and the Master followed.\n\nOnce, traveling from Jirisan through Nanyuan to Gwijeong Monastery, its abbot Hyungkak had dreamed that someone appeared saying, \"Tomorrow the Master of the Lotus Dharma across three lives shall arrive. Prepare and welcome him.\" The abbot swept the courtyard and prepared food. When the Master arrived that evening, Hyungkak related the dream. The Master also frequently dreamed of the Great Master Zhiyi teaching the Wonderful Dharma to multitudes, or sitting in meditation in Hwahjang Hermitage, firmly established, eventually receiving tribute even from demonic spirits. Sometimes mountain spirits would point out temple sites, or at Dragon Rock Monastery monks would dream of golden lotus thrones awaiting the Master. Such auspicious visions were numerous, yet these matters lie beyond the scope of Confucian discourse, so I shall not elaborate further.\n\nIn the spring of Taeho's eighth year, the Master took up residence at Yaksasanyaksa Hermitage on Wolsaeng Mountain. Finding the valleys crystal-clear but the buildings crumbling, he undertook repairs. Once, sitting silently in a room, cultivating subtle contemplation, he suddenly reflected: \"If I do not attain the wonderful wisdom of Tiantai, how can one escape the bonds of illness, even with Yongming's longevity of 120 years?\" This self-admonition brought realization. Later, while lecturing on the Wonderful Dharma, he reached the passage \"This mind becomes Buddha, this mind is Buddha.\" Unable to contain himself, his face burst into laughter. From then on he found joy in teaching the Wonderful Dharma, his eloquence and wisdom flowing without obstruction.\n\nHe earnestly encouraged all to practice penitential meditation. Daily he paid homage to the fifty-three Buddhas twelve times, never slackening through bitter cold or scorching heat. The monastic community came to call him \"the one who practices constant repentance.\"\n\nBelievers from Tamjin County—Choi Pyo, Choi Hong, and Lee Incheon—came to pay their respects. They said, \"The monastic community grows daily, yet our mountain dwelling is too small. In the south of our district lies the ancient site of Mandok Monastery, a place of clear and sublime beauty. Would you not go to establish a temple there?\" The Master went, surveyed the land, and agreed. In the spring of the third year of Taean, he commenced the work. He directed disciples Wonyoung, Jiddam, and Bop'an to oversee construction. More than eighty buildings were erected. By autumn of the fourth year of Jeong'yu, the temple was completed and a dedication ceremony held.\n\nNine years later, in spring, the provincial governor Bok Janghan, having heard of the Master's spiritual attainment, requested that he establish a teaching center at Baekryeon Mountain within his domain. The Master went with his disciples. Finding the land obstructed and waterless, he initially intended to return. But then, pulling up a stone, pure spring water suddenly gushed forth. Marveling, he remained for several years.\n\nIn the eleventh year, Choi Pyo and others sent word: \"Our temple's dharma assembly has long lay dormant. You cannot wander forever. We earnestly implore you.\" He returned and widely opened the teaching center.\n\nIn the summer of the renzi year, young Confucian scholars came from the capital. The Master accepted them as disciples, ordained them, and taught them the Lotus Sutra, encouraging them to master its teachings. From this time, seekers came from all directions, the assembly growing constantly.\n\nOn the eighth day of the fourth month in the jimiin year, he first established the Samantabhadra dojo, practicing the Lotus Samadhi to seek rebirth in the Pure Land, following precisely the Tiantai ritual forms. Over long years he conducted the Lotus repentance practice, and through repeated encouragement, more than a thousand people came to recite this scripture.\n\nResponding to the requests of the four groups of disciples, he traveled teaching, spreading the dharma for thirty years. Through his skillful guidance, he accepted thirty-eight disciples. He established five monasteries and hermitages. Kings, nobility, provincial governors, and magistrates—the four groups of high and low—more than three hundred people inscribed their names in his society. Through successive transmission and teaching, countless beings who heard even a single verse formed profound karmic connections.\n\nFor fifty years the Master remained hidden in the mountains, never setting foot in the capital, never involving himself in worldly affairs. His nature was marked by simplicity and integrity. His eyes never gazed at impropriety; his words never erred. He lit no lamp at night and slept without bedding. All gifts from patrons he distributed to the poor. In his quarters lay only three robes and a single begging bowl.\n\nBeyond his practice of meditation and teaching, each day he recited the entire Lotus Sutra once, chanted the Cundi mantra one thousand times, and called the name of Amitabha Buddha ten thousand times. He often reflected: \"The ocean of Buddhist scriptures is vast; students lose their way.\" Thus he compiled an essential compendium of the three great works, had it carved into printing blocks, and distributed it widely—a great aid to later generations.\n\nWhen the king heard of this, he was pleased and in due time bestowed upon the Master the title \"Seonsa.\" Subsequently, imperial edicts arrived repeatedly, with yearly provisions sent to his support.\n\nIn the fourth month of the imja year, having entrusted the temple affairs to his foremost disciple Cheonin, the Master withdrew to a separate quarters to sit in peaceful repose, devoted entirely to seeking rebirth in the Pure Land.\n\nOn the last day of the sixth month, at the time of the fasting meal, he called the steward and said: \"This old bones are oppressed by the heat and my appetite fails. I foresee a distant journey. Quickly have a bamboo meditation bench made for me.\" When it was completed, he said to the senior monks: \"This bench is light and convenient. Try sitting and you will find it quite pleasant.\"\n\nOn the third day of the seventh month, he moved to the guest quarters and showed slight signs of illness, reclining and singing:\n\n*The true nature of all phenomena,*\n*Clear and lucid, perfectly still—*\n*To speak it is to lose the principle;*\n*To show it is to abandon the teaching.*\n*Our school's one great matter of the Lotus—*\n*Understanding it subtly according to one's capacity,*\n*Is all we have.*\n\nHe also sang the Song of Original Awakening by Wonhyo:\n\n*The forms of the dharma-realm body are beyond conception,*\n*Silent, performing no action, yet leaving nothing undone.*\n*Following the Buddha-body and Buddha-mind,*\n*Inevitably we shall be reborn in that land.*\n\nWhether sitting or reclining, he continuously chanted and recited without ceasing.\n\nOn the sixth day, after bathing and changing clothes, he sat in meditation through the entire day. As evening came, he summoned Cheonin and, after entrusting him with the great principles of the Buddha-dharma, said: \"The season has turned to autumn. My departure brings no anxiety.\"\n\nWhen Cheonin asked, \"Your vital breath seems somewhat different from before—how is this?\" the Master replied: \"I have long desired to journey to the Pure Land, but the summer heat made me await the beginning of autumn. Now I shall not delay.\" He then had Bosji transcribe these final verses:\n\n*When the cock crows at midnight's hour,*\n*The perfect jewel has fulfilled its light.*\n*Those not yet awakened, hear my final word—*\n*Who opens their mouth at this very moment?*\n\nHe posted this on a pillar before his meditation bench and chanted as peacefully as always.\n\nAt the hour of the rooster on the seventh day, he had the bell struck to gather the assembly. He requested water for washing, donned his robes, ascended the platform, sat in full lotus position facing west, and addressed the gathering: \"Fifty years this worn-out thing has hidden in the mountains. Today it departs. Each of you, apply yourselves! Exert yourselves for the dharma!\"\n\nWhen Cheonin asked, \"Master, the mind in meditation at the moment of departure is itself the Pure Land. Where do you still wish to go?\" the Master replied: \"If this thought remains unmoved, enlightenment manifests right here. I go without going; they come without coming. This is the resonance of response and stimulus—in truth, nothing lies beyond the mind.\" \n\nHaving finished speaking, he ceased his recitation and entered meditation. Drawing near, all saw that his breath had ceased. He was eighty-three years old; his monastic life had spanned seventy years. His countenance remained bright and luminous, unlike that of the ordinary deceased. His hands and feet remained supple; the crown of his head remained warm long after.\n\nThe magistrate of Tamjin arrived with attendants and commissioned the painter Bak Bo to capture the Master's likeness. More than fifty members of the four groups from nearby regions rushed forward to pay their respects, all weeping tears of reverence.\n\nWhen word reached the throne, the king grieved deeply. He commanded his officials to confer upon the Master the rank of National Master, granting him the honorific title Wonmyo and his stupa the name Junggjin. A dignitary was sent bearing imperial letters to perform the rites at his temple, and the king commissioned this subject to compose the stele inscription.\n\nThough I am of humble station and limited talent, unworthy of this task, the royal command was urgent and I could not refuse. Reverently consulting the Master's record, I have set forth this preface. Now follows the inscription:\n\n*When the Crane Grove saw extinction's final mystery,*\n*The subtle truth gradually grew dim.*\n*Emptiness and form contended endlessly,*\n*Contradiction holding firm.*\n*Each claimed their partial attainment,*\n*Yet belief remained incomplete.*\n*Nagarjuna thrust aside the false,*\n*And revealed the authentic seal.*\n*Zhiyi, continuing the line,*\n*Refined and clarified through analysis.*\n*People came to know one path,*\n*And traveled it direct and straight.*\n*Our Master, true heir to this line,*\n*Mastered the three contemplations.*\n*The Samantabhadra dojo,*\n*He first established in this eastern land.*\n*Urging all to chant the Lotus,*\n*The reciters grow day by day.*\n*Ah, the Master's heart was firm,*\n*Strong and unwavering.*\n*Not lured by profit or fame,*\n*No demon or heretic could approach.*\n*Standing solitary in the realm,*\n*He lit the patriarch's torch.*\n*His insight was clear and complete,*\n*Yet his practice of repentance grew ever more intense.*\n*That he delayed death and awaited the season*\n*Was no deception or trick.*\n*The illumination of mind comes at the rooster's crow;*\n*The funeral rite flourishes in autumn's ease.*\n*Though my brush is dull and my words unpolished,*\n*The Master's whole life*\n*Leaves no shame when carved in stone.*\n*Though this mountain may crumble,*\n*This name shall never change.*"
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The three vehicles (三乘) refer to the Shravakayana (path of hearers), Pratyekabuddhayana (path of solitary realizors), and Bodhisattvayana (path of bodhisattvas)—three paths by which sentient beings cross the sea of suffering.
  - key: ''
    value: The Twin Grove (雙林) is where the Buddha entered final nirvana.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The three contemplations (三觀) are the foundational meditative practices of the Tiantai school: contemplation of emptiness, contemplation of provisional existence, and contemplation of the mean.'
  - key: ''
    value: Yongming (永明) refers to the renowned Chan master Yongming Yanshou (904-975), celebrated for his longevity and synthesis of Pure Land and Chan practices.
  - key: ''
    value: The Samantabhadra dojo (普賢道場) is a ritual assembly dedicated to the Bodhisattva Samantabhadra, emphasizing practice of the Lotus Sutra and Pure Land devotion.
  - key: ''
    value: The four groups (四衆) of disciples refer to monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.
  - key: ''
    value: The term 'resonance and stimulus' (感應道交) is a classical Buddhist philosophical concept describing how enlightened beings and sentient beings meet through spontaneous spiritual attunement rather than through physical causation.
